-ACES_a10.description: Picture an animal or plant that you know either is or isn’t indigenous to your region. If it’s not, try to tell us where it’s from!
-ACES_a10.name: Native or Not?

-ACES_a38.description: Observations made without having a specific activity
-ACES_a38.name: Free Observation

-ACES_a39.description: Here in the Rocky Mountains, and especially in Aspen, snowfall is very important. ACES does its best to observe snow accumulation and melt in an effort to better understand our local climate. You can contribute to our study by taking a picture of the measuring stick and recording the temperature.
-ACES_a39.name: Snow Study

-ACES_a40.description: Here at ACES we are very interested in how our ecological landscape changes over time. To participate in our study, simply take a picture of Red Mountain from the designated position. Observations like yours will help ACES monitor foliage cover and snowfall on the mountain.
-ACES_a40.name: Red Mountain

-ACES_a8.description: Do you have a question about a plant or animal that you see? Take a photo and/or ask your question here and an ACES naturalist will be in touch with you later by e-mail.

-ACES_a9.description: Find evidence of as many different kinds of bird or animal as you can!

-KJqQk6UqGuoXGfkxCMV.content:
I think there should be a way to differentiate users of different kinds, maybe through a badge system that shows up wherever a user's name and avatar do?

There's a few key benefits from something like this:
  * Seeing who's a member of the research team, for the purposes of customer service, feedback and moderation.
  * Seeing who's a member of our community partner organisations.
  * Later on we can reward users for consistent participation through badges (Note for the NN team: this can tie into our existing internal desire to distinguish peripheral, casual and core uses -- for details on what that means check out our research site at http://research.nature-net.org/ )

What do people think?
